716	5466416a-6519-4b1d-b2a2-4572da144e95	2	Instructor(s): Muhammad Rauf Butt, Muhammad Arif Butt, PhD \n3 Common Web Application Vulnerabilities https://owasp.org/Top10/ ΓÇó Injection Vulnerabilities: These occur when untrusted data is sent to an interpreter as part of a query or command, allowing an attacker to manipulate the interpreter's actions. o SQL Injection (SQLi): Exploiting unvalidated user input to manipulate SQL queries. o Cross-Site Scripting (XSS): Injecting malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. o Command Injection: Injecting commands to execute on the server via input fields. o LDAP Injection: Manipulating Lightweight Directory Access Protocol queries through user input to access unauthorized information. ΓÇó Authentication & Session Management Vulnerabilities: These vulnerabilities allow attackers to impersonate legitimate users or hijack user sessions. o Broken Authentication: Weaknesses in login mechanisms that allow attackers to bypass authentication. o Session Hijacking: Stealing or predicting session tokens to impersonate a user. o Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF/XSRF): Trick a user into submitting a request they did not intend, potentially altering user data. o Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR): Manipulating URL parameters to access data or resources without proper authorization. ΓÇó Input Validation Vulnerabilities: These vulnerabilities arise when user input is not properly validated, allowing attackers to submit unexpected or malicious data. o Cross-Site Scripting (XSS): Where user input is not sanitized, allowing malicious scripts to be executed in other users' browsers. o HTML Injection: Injecting raw HTML into a page, which can manipulate the website's appearance or behaviour. o File Upload Vulnerabilities: Uploading malicious files (e.g., scripts or executables) to the server. o Remote File Inclusion (RFI): Loading remote files into the web application, leading to arbitrary code execution. ΓÇó Access Control Vulnerabilities: These are weaknesses in enforcing proper access levels, allowing users to access resources they shouldn't. o Broken Access Control: Insufficient restriction on what authenticated users can access. o Privilege Escalation: Gaining higher privileges than intended due to improper access control configurations. o Directory Traversal: Accessing files outside the intended directory by manipulating file paths. ΓÇó Security Misconfigurations: These vulnerabilities occur when web servers, applications, or databases are misconfigured, exposing unnecessary or insecure functionality. o Unpatched Software: Not applying security updates to web application components. o Default Credentials: Using factory-default usernames and passwords in production environments. o Excessive Permissions: Overly permissive file or folder access permissions on web servers. ΓÇó Denial of Service (DoS) Vulnerabilities: These allow attackers to make a web application or website unavailable to legitimate users. o Application-Level DoS: Exploiting application flaws (e.g., resource-intensive processes) to exhaust server resources. o Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS): Overloading a server with requests from multiple sources to make it unavailable.	3185	3	3	[-0.07506341,-0.0069229924,-0.08559239,0.030071998,0.0031886168,-0.07240987,0.10049423,0.021948636,-0.022872461,-0.03534567,0.031078832,0.007571208,0.099769,-0.031885643,0.0005869355,0.050014496,0.030031675,0.0030647905,-0.04699697,0.06731862,-0.033924975,0.02388294,-0.07261055,0.018848067,-0.104788594,-0.007568086,-0.035426866,-0.07037726,-0.033636417,-0.04084752,-0.04330303,0.0040351134,-0.07224917,0.02589443,-0.09161184,0.005146977,0.105153754,-0.04593597,-0.03841413,-0.07499787,-0.07626972,-0.073444456,-0.05613678,0.039138418,-0.059320584,-0.07122329,-0.031637043,-0.04820502,-0.046364993,0.018088276,-0.04655536,-0.003398421,0.012165789,0.04139046,-0.07300152,-0.1072774,-0.027460827,-0.0008847032,-0.011117442,0.066773735,-0.10640293,0.0